  <FONT SIZE="4">This Month:<BR>
PMS AND PERFORMANCE<BR>
Dr. Rick Nappi, N.D., DIHom., FBIH<BR>

</FONT>
  </TD>
  </TR>
<TR>
  <TD ALIGN="LEFT">
  <HR>
  May 1996 / Volume 1
  <HR>
  </TD>
  <TD ALIGN="CENTER">
  <HR>
  PMS AND PERFORMANCE
  <HR>
</TR>
  </TABLE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<FONT SIZE="4">Nine Out of Ten Women Suffer</FONT><BR>
from symptoms of premenstrual syndrome (PMS) . Most will be familiar with a number of the 150 symptoms associated with this condition; anxiety, depression, mood swings, bloating, weight gain, backache, and the list goes on. The monthly disruption and distress that PMS can cause women and those close to them can be devastating. For the female athlete, it makes matters even worse. When a 100th of a second can mean the difference between winning or losing, PMS can tilt the scales against you. Even the top athlete can be striped of their energy, stamina and strength over night. This has to be the most frustrating aspect in a female athlete's training and competition calendar. To combat this effectively, the band-aid approach will not do. If you wait for the symptoms to surface it is to late, for that cycle anyway. Staying up to speed is the key and making sure you incorporate the PMS calendar into your training to avoid the symptoms will be of great benefit. The bottom line here is prevention!<P>
Here is a brief description of the body chemistry involved in many PMS symptoms. Progesterone receptors normally transport the molecules of progesterone into the nucleus of cells, where progesterone can be converted and used to regulate blood sugar. It is now believed that a significant cause of PMS is progesterone receptors not functioning properly when the level of the hormone in the blood is raised, such as those days between ovulation and menstruation. So therefore the regulation of blood sugar by nutrition is a key issue in the management.<P>
Resent studies have shown that as many as 30% of severe PMS sufferers can be helped by proper nutrition alone. It is advised that PMS sufferers cut down on saturated fats from meat and dairy products; reduce intake of processed carbohydrates (white flour products) and concentrated carbohydrates (fruit juices, dried fruits), diet sodas and caffeine. You should eat more complex carbohydrates and fiber foods from vegetables, fruits, and whole grains. Complex carbohydrates, such as bread, pasta and rice, play an important role in the diet of an athlete, as they cause a gradual rise in blood sugar levels and a gradual fall. Sugar causes a rapid rise and rapid drop in blood sugar and is not the solution to the low blood sugar levels associated with PMS. Meal spacing is also a critical  part of the recommended nutritional regime. Small portions of food rich in complex carbohydrates should be eaten at 3-hour intervals during the day. Using this regime, the blood sugar levels should be balanced and many PMS symptoms relieved.
<P>
Other then nutrition, there are several other simple alternatives that can alleviate this monthly ordeal:<P>
Reflexology: A recent study revealed that women with stressful premenstrual symptoms who received ear, hand, and foot reflexology once per week for an eight week period in 30 minute sessions reported a considerable reduction in PMS symptoms and discomfort.
Magnesium Supplements have been shown to be helpful in a recent study. Taking 400mg of magnesium daily during PMS reduced pain, weight gain, and nervous tension by over 90%. 50mg of vitamin B-6 should be taken with the magnesium as this helps with absorption.
Ayurvedic; Treatments can be very effective in treating severe PMS problems. An example is a woman who had endured terrible PMS, 10 days a month, for 22 years. Various conventional drugs brought no relief. She was   then taken off certain foods and given herbs to put her in balance. She went on a special ayurvedic purification and detoxification program which took away all of her PMS symptoms.
<P>
In naturopathic medicine, the strategic use of herbs can considerably reduce or alleviate the discomfort of PMS. Here are some recommendations:
<P>
Vitus agnus-castus: (40 drops liquid extract or one capsule dried extract, once daily in the morning) to restore the normal balance of progesterone and estrogen.
<P>
Evening Primrose oil (3-4g daily with meals) to correct the imbalanced metabolism of the essential fatty acids which in turn will release the hormone prostaglandin which reduces cramps in the uterus and breast tenderness.
<P>
Milk thistle extract (420mg daily, divided into 3 doses; it should contain 70-80% silymarin) to support the liver function where excess estrogen is metabolized.
<P>
Two preventatives that work great, which I have developed for the athlete on the go:
<P>
Perfect Woman; a homeopathic medicine which will help balance and regulate the female endocrine, hematological and reproductive systems. Many report complete remission after one cycle. It also reduces symptoms of menopause.
<P>
The Perfect Meal; A whole food derived from herbs provides a complete meal. Just mix 2 scoops into your favorite liquid and drink. This is key to maintaining blood sugar levels and feeding nutrients directly to cell level. 
<P>
NOTE: Those persons that read this and utilize the program, please e-mail me with your comments and success stories, thank you.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
