<HTML>
  <HEAD>
  <TITLE>Rick Nappi, ND, DIHom/Nappi Report</TITLE>
  </HEAD>
 <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="23238e" VLINK="2f4f2f" ALINK="C40026">
  <TABLE BORDER="0">
<center>
<A HREF="/ads/ads.htm"><IMG SRC=" /images/baner1.jpg" ALT="$59 Banner"></A><P>
 </center><HR>
  <TR>
  <TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2">
  <IMG ALT="Nappi Report" SRC="/images/nappireport.gif" BORDER="0">
  </TD>
  <TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="CENTER" COLSPAN="2">
  <FONT SIZE="4">This Month:<BR>
FOOD SAFETY IN SUMMER<BR>
Dr. Rick Nappi, N.D., DIHom., FBIH<BR>

</FONT>
  </TD>
  </TR>
<TR>
  <TD ALIGN="LEFT">
  <HR>
 <B>August 1996 / Volume 4</B>
  <HR>
  </TD>
  <TD ALIGN="CENTER">
  <HR>
  <B> FOOD SAFETY IN SUMMER</B>
  <HR>
</TR>
  </TABLE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
It's summer again and everyone is breaking out the barbecue and having picnics. This picture is as American as any innocent Rockwell sculpture. However, there are more illnesses and fatalities in the summer due to contaminated food than any other time. The sad affair is that this, food contamination problem has it's most serious effects on young children. I know that we all say "it could never happen to me", but there are many parents that are sitting in the emergency room right now saying "why us". When this happens to a loved one it can traumatize the entire family, not to mention putting a damper on the weekend festivities. So once again, as I do every time this year, I will outline the steps to a safe and tasty summer without incident.<P>
Most of us think of summer food safety as the abc's that we learned as a child from our parents. Like not letting the potato salad sit in the sun, or keeping the milk in a cooler. However, times have changed and there are environmental circumstances in existence now, that either did not exist or were a low level threat in the good old days. Now we must re-think our rules governing food safety. To follow are the tips that will reduce and or eliminate the threat of food contamination, illness or death.<P>
<B>1. SAFETY STARTS AT THE SUPERMARKET.</B> Here is where much of the cross contamination will occur and spread quickly to everything at home. When you buy meats, poultry or fish, place them in one of those bags found in the produce department. Although they are sealed, some juices may leak from the package and contaminate other items in the shopping cart. So double bag it and separate it from everything else in the cart. Think about it, if you place this package in with your produce and some juice from one of these packages drips onto your vegetables, it is now contaminated and you did not even pay for it yet. When you get home and place this produce in the refrigerator, you are well on your way to contaminating everything in the refrigerator.
<B>A</B>. Select non-perishable items to be placed in the cart first so that perishable items are in the cart for a shorter time period.
<B>B.</B> Check all meat, poultry and fish packages for leakage and double wrap before placing in the cart. Keep away from fruits and vegetables and put them in a separate place in the cart.
<B>C.</B> After purchasing, go straight home. Don't run a bunch of errands while leaving food in the back seat or trunk of the car. Keep it cool!<P>
<B>2. DON'T BE FOOLED BY TIME. </B>These persistent forms of bacteria will remain alive in the refrigerator as well as the freezer. The freezer temperature will not kill this bacteria. They will simply wait for you to defrost the package and begin unleashing it's venom on everything it comes in contact with. Counter tops, hands (which will touch everything), plates, etc. So when taking meat, poultry or fish from the refrigerator or freezer, walk it directly to the sink and un-wrap it there. This is much easier to contain and clean up without cross contamination. Just make sure you wash the sink out thoroughly before washing your produce, with an anti-bacterial soap.<P>
<B>3. ASSUME THAT ALL POULTRY, FISH & MEAT </B>is contaminated. When cutting, do not use a wooden block as bacteria will hide in the grooves and scratches. Use an impervious plastic board. Never use a sponge to clean up, instead use a paper towel and throw it away at once and don't forget to clean any utensils before using it on anything else. Use an anti-bacterial soap or a solution of bleach and water. If the package says take directly from the freezer to the stove, don't even think of it. The Federal guidelines specify defrosting first, no matter what the label says. Cooking frozen foods will not ensure that all the bacteria will be killed in the center. So never go from the freezer to the stove or grill. Defrost in the refrigerator or microwave first! Remember, even if the package tells you to go directly from the freezer to the stove to cook, DON'T! This is not the position of the Department of Agriculture food safety personal.<P>
<B>4. PAY ATTENTION AT THE GRILL.</B> You bring out a plate of raw hamburger and use a spatula to take it from the plate to place on the grill. You now take more raw meat from the plate to cook and then use the same spatula to remove the cooked meat from the grill. You have just contaminated the cooked meat with the juices from the uncooked meat you just placed on the grill. And please do not put the cooked meat on the same plate with the uncooked meat or juices. Use two different spatulas and plates.
<B>A. </B>Cook all meat and poultry until all the juices run clear, not red or pink.
<B>B</B>. Cook all meat and poultry until there is no pink in the center.<P>
<B>5. BEWARE OF RE-PACKAGED MEAT, POULTRY & FISH.</B> Did you know that most states allow stores to remove these items from the shelves upon expiration and then re-package it with a new expiration date and then put it back out on the shelf for you to buy? Don't be afraid to speak up and demand to know if your store does this. In addition, there is no research that indicates that these items bought in a butcher shop is any less contaminated then that found in the supermarket. Two or three states have passed legislation that requires markets to place an (R) on the label if they have re-packaged it. So find out if your state has passed this law and then look for the (R). If your store does not do this, look for another store to shop in.<P>
I know that this is not every tip in the book, and there are many others. However, I can write forever on this topic. These are the most important keys to keeping food safe in the summer or anytime for that matter<P>
<B>Until Next Time, STAY HEALTHY!</B><P>
<B>NOTE: Those persons that read this and utilize the program, please e-mail me with your comments and success stories, thank you.</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
