<HEAD>

<TITLE>Court TV News: Trial Report</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">

<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP
BORDER=0></A>



<H2>Trial Report</H2>



<P><I><B>Note:</B> This section only contains information about live trial(s)
currently being shown on Court TV. Information about major ongoing cases can be
found in the appropriate section of the <A HREF="/casefiles/">Casefiles</A>
area (e.g. <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/">Simpson</A>, <A
HREF="/casefiles/warcrimes/">War Crimes</A>, <A
HREF="/casefiles/unabomber/">Unabomber</A>, <A
HREF="/casefiles/oklahoma/">Oklahoma City Bombing</A>). Also look there for <A
HREF="/casefiles/verdicts/">verdicts</A> in trials previously shown on Court
TV.</I></P>



<A NAME="garcia"><HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT></A>

<H3>The Estate of Jerry Garcia v. Carolyn Adams Garcia<br>
<A HREF="update5.html">Read updates from the trial</A></H3>

<P>Jerry Garcia, leader of the Grateful Dead, sang about peace and love, but
his heirs are fighting it out in court over his money.</p>

<P>Garcia may have been making some great music in concert arenas across the
country in 1993. But years of drug abuse, combined with his bout with diabetes
rendered him susceptible to his second wife's bullying when he agreed to a $5
million divorce settlement, the Garcia estate claims. (<A
HREF="/library/newsmakers/wills/garcia.html">Garcia's will</A> is in the Court
TV library.)</P>

<P>Carolyn Adams Garcia, known as "Mountain Girl," met Jerry in 1964. They
became lovers two years later and continued a steady live-in relationship until
1975, with their two children -- Annabella and Theresa -- and Carolyn daughter,
Sunshine, from a previous marriage with Ken Kesey, author of "One Flew Over the
Cuckoo's Nest." They remained friends after the break-up and married in 1981.
But the couple didn't live together until Jerry was hospitalized in 1986 for
diabetes. They separated in 1990.</P>

<P>When a separation was initiated, Jerry agreed to pay $24,000 in monthly
family support. Frustrated by the slow pace of the legal action, the two met in
the office of David Hellman, Jerry's longtime personal attorney and
accountant, with no lawyers present. Jerry allegedly wanted Carolyn to tell him
what she wanted so they could finalize a property agreement and proceed with
the divorce. She said she offered two proposals: the first called for a joint
accounting of all their assets -- including Jerry's record business -- which
Jerry rejected. Her second proposal was for Jerry to pay her $5 million over 
20 years, at no less than $250,000 a year, she said. He agreed to the second
option and payments of $20,833 a month ($250,000 divided by 12) were set up in
January of 1994. </P>

<P>The marriage was dissolved, although no final judgment was entered by the
court because community property issues remained at the time of Jerry's death.
Nevertheless, Jerry was free to marry Deborah Koons on Feb. 14, 1994. The
monthly payments to Carolyn under the $5 million agreement continued until
Jerry's death in August of 1995. According to the estate, Jerry had been
taking steps to rescind the agreement.

<P><B>The Estate </B><BR>
Court documents reveal only hints of the value of the estate. Jerry' Garcia's 1993
earnings exceeded $3 million, more than half of which was earned from touring
with the Grateful Dead. His estate allegedly earns up to $250,000 a year from
Ben & Jerry's Ice Cream to use the "Cherry Garcia" name for one of its flavors.
Income from the "J. Garcia" line of fashion ties and Grateful Dead merchandise
has not been disclosed but is believed to be considerable.</P>

<P><B>The Defense's Argument</B><BR>
Carolyn Adams Garcia says that contrary to the estate's claim, her husband was
in very good physical and mental condition -- and knew exactly what he was
doing -- when he entered into the agreement. Although they met at Hellman's
office, Hellman was not acting as Jerry's attorney, a point the estate
will challenge. Though they lived apart, the Garcias were happily married for
many years, they vacationed together, he took her on his tours, and they
planned to buy a home in Marin County, Calif., she says, claiming they lived
apart only because of tax problems.</P>

<P><B>The Plaintiff's Argument</B><BR>
The estate plans to offer expert testimony to show that Jerry's drug addiction
left him in a state of "hyper-suggestibility," a condition in which a person
can be easily manipulated. Combine that condition with the bullying and
conspiratorial tactics of Hellman and the defendant and you have a person who
didn't knowingly enter into an agreement, the estate says.</P>

<P>The estate also says Carolyn and Jerry Garcia's marriage was a phony, a
mere tax shelter for Jerry.  Hellman was working on setting up Carolyn with a
home in Oregon even before the marriage, the estate says. They took out a
confidential marriage certificate so their friends and the public wouldn't
think it strange that the two remained living apart. The estate promises to
produce witnesses to refute Carolyn's claim that although she lived separately
from Jerry, she often toured with the band. The estate will contend that since
the couple never lived as man and wife, their community property is scant.</P>



<P>Furthermore, the estate claims the agreement is just a step toward a final
settlement, which was never reached, rather than an enforceable contract.</P>


<p><A HREF="update5.html">Read updates from the trial.</A></P>
