<html><head><title>Professor Arthur Miller's Courtroom Challenge</title>
</head><body bgcolor=ffffff text=000000 link=0000FF vlink=8e2323>
<center><img width=517 height=142 src=/graphics/ctv/chall.gif></center>
<blockquote>
<h3>Welcome to the Courtroom Challenge.</h3>  
<b>
I'll present you with real landmark cases decided by the Supreme Court and other
courts around  the country. You can explore the facts, research the law, consider
various arguments and then either decide the case or argue one side or the other.
I'll tell you how the real case came out -- but not until after you have made up
your mind about what should have happened. <p>If you argue one side of the case,
you'll get points for choosing facts, cases and arguments that best support your
side, whether or not your client ultimately wins. Enjoy the advocacy process! 

I hope you will learn something interesting about the law along the way.
<P>
Professor Arthur Miller<BR>
<I>Harvard Law School</I>


<p>We'll be adding new cases to the system on a regular basis.  We start with the
following:</b><p>

<B>

<a href="pledge/casef1.htm"><img width=32 height=22 align=top border=0
src=/graphics/ctv/stonbull.gif>Mandatory Allegiance - When the Pledge Affronts
Faith</a><P>

