<HTML>


<HEAD>


<TITLE>Court TV News</TITLE>


</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">


<A HREF="/map/news.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/news.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>


<BR CLEAR=ALL>





<!--ÇPÈÇA HREF="/live/"ÈWhat's On Court TV Now.Ç/AÈÇBRÈ


Images updated every minute from a live Court TV video feed! Also, hear the audio feed in ÇA HREF="http://www.realaudio.com"ÈRealAudioÇ/AÈ format.Ç/PÈ-->





<!--ÇPÈÇA HREF="http://www.abcradionet.com/sound/ctv.ram"ÈThe Court TV Legal MinuteÇ/AÈÇBRÈ





Interesting legal stories in ÇA HREF="http://www.realaudio.com"ÈRealAudioÇ/AÈ format, brought to you by the Court TV Law Center and ÇA HREF="http://www.abcradionet.com"ÈABCRadioNetÇ/AÈ.Ç/PÈ-->





<P><A HREF="/library/hotdocs/">Hot Documents</A><BR>


Follow the paper trail in the tobacco litigation war, download transcripts and depositions from the Simpson civil trial, and read other legal documents that make headlines.</P>





<P><A HREF="report.html#garcia">Trial Report: The Estate of Jerry Garcia v. Carolyn Adams Garcia <BR></A>





The widow of Grateful Dead legend Jerry Garcia is contesting a paragraph-long document in which Garcia's second wife, Carolyn Adams Garcia, was granted $5 million of his estate.</P>





<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>





<H3>News Highlights</H3>


<P><A HREF="106c.html">Lighting Up, But Not Laid Back</a><BR>
A half-dozen clubs have quietly sprouted up in San Francisco over the last five months, supplying marijuana to people who claim it alleviates the symptoms of their illnesses. The clubs, which might have been expected to experience newfound freedom when voters approved Proposition 215 in November, have instead functioned like fortresses under fire.</P>

<P><A HREF="106b.html">Firm Has Friends on Both Sides of Apple-Next Merger</a><BR>
Apple Computer Inc.'s recent reunion with co-founder Steven Jobs and his company, Next Software Inc., was a prime example of how quickly business alliances change in Silicon Valley. But the $400 million merger also illustrates how lawyers often change sides in the volatile high-tech world.</P>


<P><A HREF="106a.html">Tobacco Takes a Hit</a><BR>
A federal judge rejects a bid by the tobacco giants to bar the state from suing them, clearing the way for a state court slugfest.</P>


<P><A HREF="1230d.html">The Tale of Victims' Rights</a><br>

The victims' rights movement saw substantial legislative victories in 1996. Implementation of these legislative successes, however, left much to be desired. If 1996 was a winning year for victims at the voting booth and in the legislatures, it was all too often a losing year for them in court.</P>


<P><A HREF="1230c.html">New Gingrich Counsel: A Rough Welcome</a><br>
 House Speaker Newt Gingrich's new lawyer in his ethics investigation, J. Randolph Evans, is a longtime Gingrich friend and adviser who is no stranger to tough political fights. His newest assignment may be his toughest yet, as evidenced by the fact that he began drawing fire before he'd even settled into the job. </P>

<P><A HREF="1230b.html">Escape Routes Slamming Shut for Inmates on Death Row</a><br>

Twenty years after the U.S. Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty, impatient lawmakers in April drastically cut back on death row appeals. Then, for good measure, Congress did away with the 20 federal law offices that help represent the condemned. Law-and-order enthusiasts say the system is finally free to punish murderers as demanded by justice. But advocates for death row inmates warn that the slashing of safeguards is pushing the nation toward an indiscriminate jump in executions, and that inevitably some who die will be innocent.</P>



<P><A HREF="1223d.html">Gun Ban Snares Cops</a><BR> 


A tough new federal law that bars anyone convicted of misdemeanor spousal abuse from owning or carrying a gun is creating chaos in police and sheriff's departments across the country.</P>

<P><A HREF="1223c.html">Why Can't the Condemned Die Without a Fuss?</a><BR>


Georgia Attorney General Michael J. Bowers gets a lot of press complaining that those on death row are constantly monkeying with the courts to delay justice. No question that, for most condemned prisoners, the idea is to stay alive as long as possible, and that means manipulating the system to do so. But what really clogs up the works is when long after the conviction and sentencing some judge or panel of judges decides that the guy's trial was unfair in the first place. Commentary by Ann Woolner.</P>

<P><A HREF="1223b.html"> California High Court to Weigh In on Public Access to Civil Trials</a><br>


As the debate rages on over cameras in the courts, the California Supreme Court on December 18 took up a broader proposition: whether all the media -- and the public as well -- have a constitutional right to attend civil trials. </P>


<P><A HREF="cochran.html">Johnnie Cochran, Nancy Grace Join Court TV</A><BR>

A live, weeknight talk show, "Cochran & Grace," premiers Jan. 13 on Court TV. The one-hour program will be co-anchored by Atlanta prosecutor Nancy Grace and Los Angeles lawyer Johnnie L. Cochran, Jr.</P>

