<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: O.J. Simpson Civil Case - Depositions & Documents</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">

<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>



<H2>The O.J. Simpson Civil Case: Depositions and Documents</H2>



<P><A HREF="depositions/"><B>Pre-Trial Depositions</B></A></P>



<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>

<P><a href="custodyrule.html"><B>Custody Case Ruling</b></a><BR>
The Brown family failed to show clear and convincing  evidence that O.J. Simpson's custody of his children with Nicole Brown Simpson would be detrimental to the youngsters, according to Orange County Superior Court Judge Nancy Wieben Stock in this Dec. 20, 1996 ruling. "The children share a relationship with their father that appears to be strong, positive, and healthy, with powerful psychological bonding," the judge writes. "All experts who had the benefit of analyzing the children with all of their significant adults, came to the same conclusion on this point.'' Read the <A HREF="brownstate.html">Brown family</A>'s and <A HREF="ojstate.html">O.J. Simpson</A>'s reactions to the rulings. <I>Please note: the custody battle is a separate action from the wrongful death suit.</i></P>

<P><a href="chase.html"><B>Bronco Ride Transcript</b></a><BR>

Here is the transcript of the conversation between O.J. Simpson and L.A. police detective Tom Lange during the infamous slow-speed Bronco ride on June 17, 1994.





<P><A HREF="planted2.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Bar Claims Of Planted Evidence</b><BR></a>

The plaintiffs claim that Simpson has produced no evidence to back up his "wild, desperate assertion" that incriminating evidence was planted. "In the criminal trial, Simpson was given unfettered reign to advance his unsubstantiated claims of police conspiracy . . . presumably to afford him the widest possible discretion to raise doubts in the face of a double murder prosecution against him. We are now in a civil case, however, and the rules are different," Fredric Goldman's lawyer Daniel Petrocelli states in this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion. "Evidence that creates only a 'reasonable doubt' is insufficient."</P>



<P><A HREF="rockbld.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Bar Claims Of Planted Rockingham Evidence</b><BR></a>

The LAPD collected blood drops at O.J. Simpson's Rockingham estate and found that the blood match Simpson's blood, the plaintiffs contend. In this motion filed Aug. 26, 1996, the Goldman family asks the judge to prohibit the defense from advancing its theory that blood collected from Rockingham was planted in a conspiracy to frame Simpson, arguing that "the undisputed evidence -- that the vial of Simpson's blood evidence had been collected -- renders any such speculative theory logically impossible."</P>



<P><A HREF="altrock.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Bar Claims Of Planted Glove </b><BR></a>

The plaintiffs contend that the burden of proof in the civil case to establish by a preponderance of the evidence that the bloody glove found at O.J. Simpson's Rockingham estate and other incriminating items were planted. "Simpson's evidence . . . is such that no reasonable jury could find that Simpson has met his burden of proof on this issue," Daniel Petrocelli, attorney for Fredric Goldman, states in this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion.</P>



<P><A HREF="bronco.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Bar Claims Of Planted Bronco Evidence</b><BR></a>

Since "no reasonable jury could find that Simpson has met burden of proof" to establish that blood evidence was planted, the only purpose presenting such evidence could serve is to "unnecessarily prolong the trial, confuse the issues, and mislead,"  the jury with argument that the...Bronco blood...was planted," Daniel Petrocelli, attorney for Fredric Goldman, states in this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion.</P>



<P><A HREF="faye.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Bar Evidence Of Faye Resnick's Drug Use</b><BR></a>

In a video released earlier this year and in a pretrial deposition, Simpson claims that Nicole's murder is possibly related to Faye Resnick and the debts incurred from Resnick's drug use. In this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion, the plaintiffs assert that Simpson has provided no evidence to support this claim and ask the judge to prohibit defense arguments that Resnick's used drugs led to the murders at Bundy. </P>



<P><A HREF="custody.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Permit Chain Of Custody Evidence</b><BR></a>

Plaintiffs' attorneys ask in this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion that they be allowed to establish the chain of custody of blood, hair and other physical evidence through LAPD criminalists Gregory Matheson and Susan Brockbank. In doing so, the plaintiffs would apparently avoid the testimony of criminalist Dennis Fung and other witnesses that hampered the prosecution in the criminal trial.</P>



<P><A HREF="fuhrman.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Bar Fuhrman's Invoking Of 5th Amendment</b><BR></a>

The plaintiffs wants to bar any evidence relating to former LAPD Detective Mark Fuhrman's invocation of the Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination during his deposition in the civil trial and during the Simpson criminal trial. Lawyers argue that presenting such evidence "would only invite the jury to make an improper inference." This is the Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion.</P>



<P><A HREF="racism.html"><B>Plaintiff Motion To Bar Evidence Of Fuhrman's Racism</b><BR></a>

Daniel Petrocelli asks the court to bar evidence of former Detective Mark Fuhrman's alleged racist statements and conduct.  He maintain that the "theory that Fuhrman planted the bloody glove...is not based on admissible evidence...and the evidence of racism is substantially outweighed by its tendency to prejudice the jury and unduly delay the trial." This motion was filed on Aug. 26, 1996.</P>



<P><A HREF="diary.html"><B>Defense Motion on Nicole's Journal Entries and Therapists</b><BR></a>

Nicole Brown Simpson's alleged journal entries and statements she may have made to therapists Dr. Susan Forward and Jennifer Ameli are hearsay and should not be allowed to be admitted into evidence, the defense contends in this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion.</P>



<P><A HREF="discord.html"><B>Defense Motion to Bar Evidence of Domestic Discord</b><BR></a>

Stating that "the death of Nicole Brown Simpson bears none of the traditional signs of spousal homicide," the defense asks the judge to bar the plaintiffs from introducing evidence of domestic discord in the Simpson marriage. This would include the Oct. 25, 1993 call to 911 and the "Zlomsowitch incident," when O.J. Simpson allegedly spied on his wife engaging in sex with another man. The defense contends that "evidence that a defendant has previously committed crimes or other bad acts is not admissible to prove how the defendant acted on a particular occasion, or to prove his propensity to commit the offense with which he had been charged," under the California Evidence Code. The defense claims that the plaintiffs' objective with this evidence is to unfairly prejudice the jury against Simpson. This pretrial motion was filed Aug. 26, 1996.</P>



<P><A HREF="fidelity.html"><B>Defense Motion to Preclude Evidence of Infidelity and Drug Use</b><BR></a>

The defense argues that the introduction of evidence of O.J. Simpson's alleged drug use or adultery would be inadmissible in the civil action because it's immaterial and would be prejudicial. Simpson's lawyers accuse the plaintiffs of attempting "character assassination" on their client. Though Al Cowlings admits that he saw Simpson use cocaine, the defense points out that that was more than seven years before the murders and that Simpson has no criminal record for drug use. In regard to allegations of infidelity, the defense claims that these are irrelevant because the Simpsons were divorced and had not been living together for more than two years before the murders. This is the Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion.</P>



<P><A HREF="opinions.html"><B>Defense Motion to Bar Witnesses' Opinions</b><BR></a>

Defense lawyers accuses the plaintiffs of "playing to the media" in the discovery phase of the case. In this Aug. 26, 1996, pretrial motion, they say plaintiffs' lawyers deliberately asked potential witnesses for personal opinions on whether O.J. Simpson is guilty of murdering his former wife and Ronald Goldman in an effort to manufacture soundbites in the media and infect the jury pool. The defense says such opinions are irrelevant and should be excluded from the trial. </P>



<P><A HREF="psychol.html"><B>Defense Motion to Preclude Psychologists and Psychological Terms</b><BR></a>

Nicole Brown Simpson should not be characterized as a "battered wife," O.J. Simpson should not be described as a "stalker" in the wrongful death trial, argues the defense in this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion. These terms, used by psychologists, are also widely used by the general public and have picked up "a strong secondary meaning which itself will have a prejudicial impact" on the jury. The defense also asks that the plaintiffs not be allowed to call psychologists that would provide a psychological "profile" of the defendant.</P>



<P><A HREF="record.html"><B>Defense Motion to Bar Nicole's Police Statements</b><BR></a>

Nicole Brown Simpson's alleged statement to police on New Year's Eve in 1989 that O.J. Simpson was "going to kill her" is inadmissible because it is not part of the official police record, defense lawyers maintain. They argue that statements not on the official record can only be entered if they are made spontaneously to the police. "There is no indication that any of Brown's  . . . statements to the police were blurted out spontaneously; rather, she was responding to questioning and was not so traumatized, or in physical distress, that she was unable to reflect on the statements that she made," according to this Aug. 26, 1996 motion.</p>



<P><A HREF="worth.html"><B>Defense Motion to Bar Evidence of Simpson Financial Condition</B><BR></a>

In this Aug. 26, 1996 pretrial motion, defense lawyers ask that the plaintiffs be barred from introducing evidence concerning O.J. Simpson's financial condition. They say that such evidence is prejudicial and irrelevant until the plaintiffs prove Simpson is liable for punitive damages. </P>



<P><A HREF="planted.html"><B>Plaintiff Declaration Against Planted Evidence Theory</B><BR></a>

Daniel Petrocelli, attorney for the Goldman family, argues in this Aug. 26, 1996 declaration that the defense does not have sufficient evidence to support its theory that evidence linking O.J. Simpson to the crime scene was planted. </P>



<P><A HREF="asstmotion.html"><B>Motion to Bar Accounts of Simpson Financial Assistance</B><BR></a>

The Brown family does not want the jury to hear any accounts that O.J. Simpson provided financial assistance. In this Aug. 26, 1996 motion, John Quinlan Kelly argues that "The true reason that such evidence may be offered by Mr. Simpson's counsel is to improperly bolster Mr. Simpson's character and stature in the eyes of the jury."</p>



<P><A HREF="salemotion.html"><B>Motion to Bar Accounts of Sales of Nicole's Items</B><BR></a>

Dominique Brown reportedly admitted in her deposition that she sold topless photos of her slain sister to a supermarket tabloid for several thousand dollars. In this Aug. 26, 1996 motion, John Quinlan Kelly, the Brown family's lawyer, asks that the jury not be allowed to hear any reference to the sale of Nicole's items or stories about her. "This alleged evidence is entirely irrelevant to the assessment of witness credibility in this case," Kelly states. "That the Brown's may have sold items, stories or materials to the media has absolutely nothing to do with the substantive issues of this lawsuit."</P> 



<P><A HREF="tvorder.html"><B>Order Barring TV Coverage</B><BR></a>

Pointing to what he described as the "circus atmosphere" of the Simpson murder trial, Judge Hiroshi Fujisaki banned TV cameras from the courtroom in the civil trial. In this Aug. 23, 1996 order, the judge also upholds the "gag order" preventing lawyers, witnesses and other parties involved in the trial from speaking publicly about the case.</P>



<P><A HREF="goldcomp.html"><B>The Goldman Family's Wrongful Death Action</B></A><BR>

Fred and Kimberly Goldman, murder victim Ronald Goldman's father and sister, brought this civil complaint against O.J. Simpson. Ronald Goldman's mother, Sharon Rufo, who reportedly hadn't seen him for 14 years prior to his June 12, 1994 murder, brought a separate action against Simpson. The cases have been consolidated.</P>



<P><A HREF="browncomp.html"><B>The Brown Family's Wrongful Death Action</B></A><BR>

Louis Brown, Nicole Brown Simpson's father, filed this wrongful death action against O.J. Simpson.</P>



<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>



