         6     and spell your name for the record.

         7            THE WITNESS:  My first name is Frederic,

         8     F-r-e-d-e-r-i-c, Rieders, R-i-e-d-e-r-s.

         9

        10                       DIRECT EXAMINATION

        11     BY MR. BLASIER:

        12            Q.    Dr. Rieders, you are a forensic

        13     toxicologist?

        14            A.    Yes.

        15            Q.    Can you tell the jury what that means?

        16            A.    A toxicologist -- a toxicologist is a

        17     professional in the field of -- you might say poisons,

        18     except that everything is a poison when it's too much.

        19                  So the toxicologist concerns himself with

        20     the analysis of foreign compounds, usually in

        21     biological materials, but also inanimate materials,

        22     with the effect of chemical substances that are

        23     harmful for man and, with the way that man handles

        24     those chemical substances; what the chemicals do to

        25     the body and what the body does to the chemicals.

        26                  I said "man."  Men of course, it is also

        27     applied to other areas, such as veterinary toxicology,

        28     ecological toxicology, et cetera.  But the science
 


                                                                   120
         1     arose from the study of the interaction between

         2     chemicals and man, along the line of harm.

         3                  "Forensic" refers to the application of

         4     toxicology to things that have to do with the open

         5     court -- in Latin, it's call the forensic arena -- and

         6     so it does deal with the application to legal

         7     proceedings, to various other things which may not

         8     involve legal proceedings, but making of law from a

         9     legislature.

        10                  And in many cases, the evaluation of

        11     substances as to their safety and potential

        12     harmfulness, which then may become legal issues,

        13     although they're not always -- some are medical, but

        14     they can be come legal because they are man-made

        15     things or man intervention things.

        16                  So, really, what forensic toxicology is,

        17     in simple words, the application of chemical-harm

        18     study to legal matters.

        19            Q.    Have you been retained by the defense in

        20     this case to examine the question of whether or not

        21     there is a chemical called EDTA frequently present in

        22     some of the blood stains in this case?

        23            A.    Yes.

        24            Q.    Can you briefly tell the jury what your

        25     educational background is.

        26            A.    I'm a graduate of New York University's

        27     Washington Square College, where, after World War II,

        28     I completed my education, which I had done here and
 


                                                                   121
         1     there in the country prior to that.  I immigrated here

         2     in 1939.

         3                    My -- following military service, I

         4     returned to finish my education under the GI Bill.  I

         5     received a bachelor's -- bachelor of arts degree from

         6     New York University in 1948.  No.  I'm sorry.  19 --

         7     Yes, in '48.

         8                  In 1940  -- My major subject was

         9     chemistry and my minor subject was biology.

        10                  In 1949, I received a master's of science

        11     degree from New York University in chemistry,

        12     primarily in -- well, in analytical chemistry -- that

        13     was my specialization -- and in particular,

        14     toxicological chemistry.

        15                  I was at the same time a trainee in

        16     forensic toxicology in the medical examiner's office

        17     in New York.

        18                  Following that, I received a special

        19     fellowship to the Jefferson Medical College in

        20     Philadelphia, its division of graduate studies, not

        21     towards a medical degree, but a doctor of philosophy

        22     degree, which was in the graduate division of the

        23     school.  And in 1951, I completed the requirements.

        24     And in early  I received the degree in 1952, doctor of

        25     philosophy.  My major subject was pharmacology and

        26     toxicology.

        27                    Pharmacology is the study of the

        28     interaction between chemicals and man.  In the medical
 


                                                                   122
         1     school, it is mostly centered on the interaction of

         2     medicinal substances.

         3                    In man, only, in a very general plane,

         4     how to prescribe and how to use.

         5                    Toxicology is that part of pharmacology

         6     which deals specifically with the harmful effects of

         7     chemicals.  And then, of course, that, of course, is

         8     broader than just medicine; it includes nonmedicine

         9     substances.  That was my major subject.  And my minor

        10     subject was pathology, the study of disease, and

        11     physiology, the study of the functions of the human

        12     body.

        13                    That I wrote a -- did research and

        14     wrote a doctoral thesis on toxicology, and in 1952,

        15     was awarded the degree of doctor of philosophy.

        16            Q.    Dr. Rieders, you are currently the

        17     founder and director of a laboratory called National

        18     Medical Services; is that correct?

        19            A.    Yes.

        20            Q.    Can you tell the jury very briefly what

        21     your employment experience prior to start of that

        22     laboratory.

        23            A.    My employment was quite varied.

        24                  Of course, when I came here as an

        25     immigrant, I was anything from a steam blower to a

        26     glass blower, to a dish washer.  You know what I mean;

        27     in 1939 that was a different time as far as relevance

        28     to this field is concerned.  And experience -- the
 


                                                                   123
         1     experiences I had in the area, not particularly just

         2     toxicology, but of the medical sciences.

         3                  I was a surgical technician and as a --

         4     as a company aid man in World War II in Europe, which

         5     gave me some background.  I -- during my last year

         6     working for a bachelor's degree in New York, I

         7     obtained a position with the Office of the Chief

         8     Medical Examiner of New York as a trainee.  And as a

         9     junior toxicologist, actually being trained in the

        10     methods and procedures of autopsy tissue analysis in

        11     the toxicology division.

        12                  I left there after two years to complete

        13     my -- to work for my doctorate in Philadelphia.  That

        14     was a special fellowship in which I did perform some

        15     service work for the hospital of Jefferson -- Thomas

        16     Jefferson Hospital, along the lines of toxicology

        17     because I had some training in it.

        18                  Also as a teaching assistant and mainly

        19     in toxicology, although some pharmacology.

        20                  After completing the doctoral degree, I

        21     became a teacher at Jefferson and an instructor the

        22     department of pharmacology and industrial medicine,

        23     with the emphasis on industry, a pharmacologist, and I

        24     taught medical students, graduate students.  Conducted

        25     research and published research on that I did, in

        26     addition to continuing some of the service work until

        27     I trained some other people to take over in the

        28     hospital laboratory.
 


                                                                   124
         1                  In 1956, the City of Philadelphia changed

         2     from coroner to medical examiner.  And the first

         3     medical examiner of the city required the services of

         4     a full-time toxicologist, whose responsibility was

         5     to -- to actually develop a toxicology service which

         6     didn't exist there before.

         7                  And there were several candidates.  I was

         8     among them.  We were examined and I was selected for

         9     the position as chief toxicologist in the office of

        10     the medical examiner of the City of Philadelphia,

        11     which there, was in the health department.

        12                  In addition to that, I also became

        13     responsible for organizing the center and operating a

        14     poison information center.

        15                  I conducted my work for the City Medical

        16     Examiner's Office, servicing some of the hospitals in

        17     emergency toxicology and in other areas in the poison

        18     information center, but mainly in developing and

        19     carrying out, and then supervising the analyses of

        20     autopsy specimens for foreign substances, which helped

        21     them to delineate cause of death, manner of death,

        22     circumstances, et cetera.

        23                  At the same time, I retained my

        24     affiliation with Jefferson and am still a full

        25     professor, although now I'm an adjunct until I have a

        26     teaching loan, 'cause most of my time is spent there.

        27                  And I continue to teach and train at

        28     Jefferson.  I still do that.
 


                                                                   125
         1                  This went from 1956, when I became chief,

         2     until 1970, when I founded and started an independent

         3     toxicological laboratory and consulting company,

         4     National Medical Services.

         5                  I no longer own the company; it is owned

         6     by my family.  I turned over my share of ownership and

         7     direction of the company over to them.  I am

         8     laboratory director, and of course, since it's a

         9     family business, I'm also Chairman of the Board,

        10     whatever that means.

        11                  And so I continue to, except for

        12     administrative duties, to be active in the field of

        13     toxicology, both professionally and as a teacher.

        14            Q.    Dr. Rieders, have you testified as an

        15     expert in courts across the country on the subject of

        16     toxicology?

        17            A.    Yes.

        18            Q.    Approximately how many times?

        19            A.    Well over 100 times.  I really don't know

        20     how many times.

        21            Q.    Have some of those times been for the

        22     prosecution in criminal cases and sometimes for the

        23     defense?

        24            A.    Predominantly prosecution.

        25            Q.    And National Medical Services,

        26     approximately how many employees do you have now?

        27            A.    It now has 120 employees.

        28            Q.    And do you do a lot of work -- or what's
 


                                                                   126
         1     called reference work for other labs, do various law

         2     enforcement agencies send you work to do?

         3            A.    Yes.  That's our major source of work, is

         4     reference work for other large clinical laboratories.

         5     We do the toxicology for them, as specialists.

         6            Q.    Now, in the past, have you been consulted

         7     by Special Agent Roger Martz of the  FBI?

         8            A.    Yes.  We have known each other for some

         9     years.  We've worked together, and still do.

        10            Q.    He performed some testing in this

        11     particular case on certain blood stains?

        12            A.    Yes.

        13            Q.    Do you have -- still have a professional

        14     relationship with Special Agent Martz?

        15            A.    Very much.  Still working on cases

        16     together.

        17            Q.    Now, could you tell the jury which blood

        18     stains were analyzed in this case by the FBI?

        19            A.    The blood stains that were analyzed by

        20     the FBI that I became concerned with -- they may have

        21     analyzed others, which I don't know -- are stains

        22     which I was told originated from the back gate at

        23     Mr. Simpson's home, and stains that came from a sock

        24     that was Mr. Simpson's sock, and blood stains --

        25            Q.    Now, by "back gate," do you mean back

        26     gate of 875 South Bundy?

        27            A.    At his residence, yes; Bundy.

        28            Q.    Where the murder scene was?
 


                                                                   127
         1            A.    Yes.  I'm sorry.  Yeah.  That's --

         2            Q.    Now, what technique did Special Agent

         3     Martz use to examine those stains for the presence of

         4     EDTA?

         5            A.    He used a technique which is a so-called

         6     hyphenated technique.  It consists of essentially

         7     three -- four separate steps that are combined into a

         8     unit.  They are not retrofitted like an instrument is

         9     to design -- to perform all four steps.

        10                  The first step is called liquid

        11     chromatography.  This consists of placing a sample

        12     into a tube which has some material in it.  That helps

        13     to separate compounds from each other, and then

        14     pushing the materials through the tube with a liquid.

        15                  In the course of that, the mixture -- a

        16     mixture of compounds becomes separated either into

        17     individual, truly individual compounds, totally

        18     separated from each other, but at least also into

        19     groups of compounds.  But you get separation in that

        20     fashion.

        21                  The effluent which comes out the other

        22     end when these substances march out in an orderly

        23     fashion, one after the other, is then transferring the

        24     substances or the liquid as it marches out to a

        25     connecting device, to another instrument.  And that is

        26     called an electro spray interface.

        27                  When material enters the electro spray

        28     interface -- this is a heated, very fine tube -- it is
 


                                                                   128
         1     heated to a high enough temperature, and all of those

         2     things that can vaporize and -- vaporize and become a

         3     vapor and march out partly as a vapor, partly either

         4     as a gas, if the material is actually made into gas,

         5     into -- or else is a very, very fine particulate

         6     spray, that is accomplished by putting a very high

         7     electric voltage charge on that tube.  And that's why

         8     it's called electro spray.

         9                  At the same time, there are two gases

        10     pass through:  One of them is around that tube, and it

        11     carries away the vapors of water and other highly

        12     volatile materials.  The other one goes through the

        13     tube and drives the vapors that stay in that path of

        14     the tube, and the very fine particles, into a piece of

        15     equipment called a mass spectrometer.

        16                  The best way that I can explain to you a

        17     mass spectrometer is that, it is a device which, as a

        18     molecule, or as molecules comes into -- into that

        19     device, it weighs them and it sorts them into

        20     molecules that weigh a certain amount and other

        21     molecules that weigh a different amount.

        22                    And that is fairly characteristic of a

        23     substance; it's essentially -- it's molecular weight,

        24     whether -- whatever number it is.  And there are

        25     several substances with the same number, but anyways,

        26     it's certainly a characteristic.

        27                  What it then does, though, it applies

        28     energy to the molecules, and particularly -- well, to
 


                                                                   129
         1     the molecules to such an extent that they actually

         2     break into pieces.  A molecule breaks into pieces.

         3                  It doesn't break like a beer bottle, you

         4     know, into all kinds of various bits and pieces, but

         5     more like a diamond that is being cut by a jeweler.

         6     It breaks along certain energy planes and gives

         7     predictable parts of the molecule appearing in there.

         8            Q.    Doctor, can you push the microphone away

         9     from you just a little bit?

        10            A.    From my --

        11                  Then it goes ahead and weighs the pieces.

        12     To some of these pieces, we'll add up to the sum, to

        13     the total molecule, and it displays the pieces and how

        14     many of each piece there are present.

        15                    So that you get what is called a mass

        16     spectrum, which one sees usually is lines along an

        17     axis and of certain height.

        18                  This is a picture of the molecule with

        19     whatever else was broken off at that point in time,

        20     and had appeared at the particular time at the end of

        21     the tube.  That is characteristic for a compound that

        22     we look for.

        23                  Different compounds have different times

        24     at which it takes them to march through the tube,

        25     appear, and be put into the mass spectrometer.  So by

        26     then, we have a characterization of a compound.

        27                  That -- how did we get in to it.  It was

        28     extracted, for example, with water from something,
 


                                                                   130
         1     either from tissue or from a swatch or from anything.

         2                  So it's water soluble.  We know that.

         3                  It goes through the liquid chromatograph.

         4     That means the liquid is able to push it through, and

         5     it doesn't hang up front a lot.  A lot of things hang

         6     up.  Not only that, but it takes it a certain time to

         7     get through.  That's called a retention time.  So that

         8     is another characteristic.

         9                  It's water soluble; it goes through the

        10     column; it has a given retention time; it is capable

        11     of being ionized in that -- in that electro

        12     spectrometer tube and brought into the mass

        13     spectrometer.

        14            Q.    Doctor, is there a shortcut way to

        15     describe what's going on here?

        16            A.    The rest of it, yes.

        17                         (Laughter.)

        18

        19

        20            A.    The -- one of these molecules that --

        21     well, the main molecule itself is weighed and

        22     displayed.  So you now have the weight of the

        23     molecule.  Actually, it's a little bit more than that,

        24     because it's also electrically charged.  But you know

        25     what the weight is.

        26                  Then it is broken up, and one of the

        27     pieces usually -- or two pieces, the larger pieces are

        28     filtered into another mass spectrometer, which now
 


                                                                   131
         1     breaks them up further, and goes into a third mass

         2     spectrometer, if necessary.

         3                  In this case, it only went two ways.  The

         4     first one, the molecule that came through and was

         5     filtered out is called the parent ion.  It is the

         6     parent for the next two break-up ions.

         7                  The ions which are call the daughter ion,

         8     each of these has a specified weight.  Each of these

         9     appears at the same retention time as the molecular

        10     ion, the parent ion did.  And so it's characterized

        11     as -- each one of these characterizes the substance

        12     that you're looking for.  In this case, EDTA.

        13                  So we have the characteristic of EDTA;

        14     that it was water soluble; it went through the system;

        15     it came out at a certain point in time at the end of

        16     the tube; and its molecular size at that point was

        17     weighed, was the right size to be EDTA or not;

        18     and that the break-ups, the daughter ion, also had

        19     appeared at the same retention time and weighed like

        20     characteristic pieces of EDTA.

        21                  That is how you characterize or exclude a

        22     substance.  And that is called -- the long name is

        23     liquid high performance liquid chromatograph electro

        24     spray tandem mass spectrometry tandem, but it's two

        25     mass spectrometers -- actually, three that we're

        26     dealing with here.

        27            Q.    The shortcut for that is LCESMSMS (sic)?

        28            A.    Yes.
 


                                                                   132
         1            Q.    Okay.

         2                  And is it accurate that what you're

         3     looking for if you're trying to identify whether EDTA

         4     is present in something, you're looking for the

         5     retention time; you're looking for whether it's water

         6     soluble; you're looking for whether it has the right

         7     molecular weight; and you're looking for whether the

         8     pieces are the right size.  Correct?

         9            A.    Yes.

        10            Q.    Okay.

        11            Q.    Let me show you a couple of charts that

        12     have been marked for identification 1216 and 1215.

