        12            Q.    (BY MR. BLASIER)  Now, Dr. Rieders, I've

        13     indicated that of the two sock stains that were

        14     tested, came up positive for EDTA and the negative

        15     control came up negative, correct?

        16            A.    Yes.

        17            Q.    And for the back gate, there were two

        18     tests for the presence of EDTA from the blood stain

        19     that -- that came back above, and there were three

        20     negative controls that came back negative, correct?

        21            A.    Yes.

        22            Q.    Now, do you have an opinion on why this

        23     negative control here showed presence of EDTA and the

        24     actual stain doesn't?

        25            A.    Yes, I do.

        26            Q.    And what's that opinion?

        27            A.    I believe that there was an accidental

        28     switch made somewhere along the line, between what was
 


                                                                   142
         1     supposed to be the negative control and what was

         2     supposed to be the bloody stain control.

         3            Q.    Is it accurate to say that all of the --

         4     The charts that were run in this run are consistent

         5     with there being EDTA present on the back gate and the

         6     sock, with the exception of these two?

         7            A.    Yes.

         8            Q.    Okay.

         9                  Now, did Special Agent Martz attempt to

        10     quantify the amount of EDTA that was located on the

        11     back gate and on the sock?

        12            A.    No.  He, according to everything that I

        13     saw in the record -- all that he told me, he did not

        14     attempt to quantify it; he merely wanted to see is

        15     there some there or isn't there any.

        16            Q.    Now, you have seen some charts that Agent

        17     Martz produced showing differences in known quantities

        18     of EDTA blood and the stains in this case?

        19            A.    Yes, I have.

        20            Q.    And do you have an opinion as to whether

        21     the analysis that was done with respect to the

        22     quantity of EDTA that was found is a valid analysis?

        23            A.    You mean on the stains and the controls

        24     that we are talking about here?

        25            Q.    Yes.  The stains and the known EDTA.

        26            A.    It's only valid qualitatively.  Let me

        27     tell you why.

        28                  There are two measures of amount.  One of
 


                                                                   143
         1     them is just the amount you know how much is on that

         2     picture here.

         3                  In order to have an idea of what that is,

         4     you have to have standards.  And the standards, as

         5     well as the sample, have to contain one additional

         6     thing.  And that is called an internal standard.

         7                  That means, in another chemical substance

         8     which is very close to the substance that you're

         9     looking for, but is sufficiently different so that it

        10     will separate from it and have a different retention

        11     time.  And the reason for that is that, particularly

        12     electro spray gives you variable amounts every time

        13     you run it.  There are slight variations and sometimes

        14     very substantial ones.

        15                  If you have an internal standard, then

        16     that is affected the same way as the chemical that

        17     you're looking for; so if there's only a low peak in

        18     one, then the other one's lower, too.  The ratio

        19     between the two remains unaffected.

        20                  So if you know how much the internal

        21     standard represents and what the ratio is, you can go

        22     back to your curve and determine what the amount is.

        23                  If you do not have that internal

        24     standard, you can -- you can guess, you know.  It's

        25     there; it's more than an amount that couldn't detect.

        26     It's less than a lot.  So it's a tiny bit of the EDTA

        27     that is there.  Now, that is amount.

        28                  The important thing is to know
 


                                                                   144
         1     concentration.  And that simply means amount perfect

         2     what.

         3                  If you take a drop of blood, a measured

         4     drop of blood, which is usually around 50 microliters,

         5     and you analyze it, and you find and use an internal

         6     standard and you calculate an amount, then you can say

         7     this is the concentration, so many nanograms, let us

         8     say, per microgram of blood.

         9                  But if you don't measure how much blood

        10     you have, that you started with, then you have no way

        11     of knowing what the concentration is.

        12                  It's like saying, you know, I've got --

        13     I've got some alcohol here; I've got a half an ounce

        14     of alcohol.  So is this from beer or is it from

        15     whiskey, or is it from wine?

        16                  You have to know how much wine or how

        17     much liquid you analyzed.  If you know how much

        18     liquid, then you know that this amount is 6 percent of

        19     the liquid.  It's probably beer if it's 50 percent of

        20     the liquid; it's probably 100-proof spirits.  But if

        21     you don't know how much of the total you had, you

        22     can't get to a concentration.

        23                  And there was no -- I saw no measurements

        24     of the amount of blood that was used in the analysis

        25     from the -- from the -- from the gate or from the

        26     socks or in the controls.

        27                  Controls, it would be zero.  You know,

        28     that's the amount that you find, which is not in
 


                                                                   145
         1     the -- nothing.  Which, in the case of blood, you have

         2     to know what's in the lower part of the equation.

         3                  The denominator, so many milligrams of

         4     micrograms per milliliter of blood or whatever you

         5     want, but you have to know how much you use to

         6     calculate that.

         7            Q.    Now, Dr. Rieders, do you have an opinion

         8     as to the source of the EDTA in the back gate stain

         9     and the sock stain?

        10            A.    To the source?

        11                  Other than the blood from a living person

        12     who has not been -- from a living person who has not

        13     received EDTA intravenously -- it is given

        14     intravenously as a treatment in lead poisoning and in

        15     other poisonings -- but normal blood, there's -- not

        16     come from someone who's had it injected into them does

        17     not contain any by this means at that level of

        18     sensitivity, detectable amount of EDTA.

        19            Q.    All right.  Do you know what a purple-top

        20     tube is?

        21            A.    Well, if you're referring to a medical

        22     laboratory purple-top tube, yes.

        23                  When you draw blood from a patient for

        24     testing, you have to draw it into a tube.  If you want

        25     to test a whole blood where it doesn't coagulate, so

        26     you put an anticoagulant in it.

        27                  There are various anticoagulants.  Of the

        28     purple tube, or sometimes called lavender-top tube is
 


                                                                   146
         1     one which has EDTA, which dries up all the calcium in

         2     the blood, and the blood won't coagulate.  So that's

         3     called EDTA blood.

         4                  That's what you do when you draw blood

         5     for various measurement purposes.

         6            Q.    Do you have an opinion whether or not the

         7     EDTA that was detected by Special Agent Martz could

         8     have come from a purple-top tube?

         9            A.    I do have an opinion.

        10            Q.    What is your opinion?

        11            A.    And that is in terms of finding in blood

        12     the most common source, unless, of course, there's

        13     some outside contamination introduced otherwise.  But

        14     the most common reasonable source is that it has to be

        15     purple-top-tube blood.

        16            Q.    Now, EDTA is used in a lot of different

        17     things, is it not?

        18            A.    Yes.

        19            Q.    And are there studies that examine the

        20     question of how much EDTA a person might have in their

        21     blood just normally, from eating food that has it in

        22     it?

        23            A.    Yes.  There have been studies very early,

        24     as a matter of fact, and with a technique that you

        25     can't even use anymore.  They won't allow you to.

        26            Q.    And do those studies indicate that the

        27     source of EDTA in this case could have come from

        28     normal ingestion of food?
 


                                                                   147
         1            A.    No, not even from abnormal ingestion.

         2                  The amount that is found -- that was

         3     found by this radioactive label technique -- that's

         4     really what it was -- was absolutely minuscule of a

         5     measure after measured amounts even greater than what

         6     we get in food today were given to people.

         7                  The reason I say it's not done now is,

         8     you can't give radioactive -- that kind of radioactive

         9     material to people to find out whether they're

        10     absorbing something.

        11            Q.    In your opinion, is there any source of

        12     EDTA other than a purple-top tube, that could account

        13     for the findings of the FBI in this case?

        14            A.    Well, contamination, of course, can --

        15     accidental, other contamination of those that were

        16     positive.

        17            Q.    And was there any indication of that in

        18     this case?

        19            A.    I really don't know where it came from,

        20     but those are the two things that I can tell you where

        21     it may come from, either from EDTA blood or from some

        22     contamination that was introduced at some point in

        23     time into the material.

        24            Q.    Now, contamination, could that have been

        25     something in the laboratory -- let me rephrase that.

        26                  There were other blank samples that were

        27     run along the stains in this case, were there not?

        28            A.    Yes.
 


                                                                   148
         1            Q.    And other than the one control that we

         2     talked about, did any of those show the presence of

         3     EDTA?

         4            A.    No.

         5            Q.    Is that consistent with the source of

         6     EDTA in this case being something other than

         7     contamination?

         8            A.    No, it really isn't.  Contamination is

         9     usually a random thing.  You know, accidental

        10     contamination, and this is not random.  You have a set

        11     of positives and a set of negatives.  With the

        12     exception of the two samples that you mentioned, and

        13     as I mentioned, my opinion is that these are switched

        14     samples, you know, one is supposed to be the other.

        15            Q.    So is there -- Is there any indication of

        16     contamination as being a source to the positive

        17     results that the FBI found in this case?

        18            A.    No.

        19            Q.    Is there a phenomenon that's known as

        20     ghosting, ghosting?

        21            A.    Ghosting.

        22            Q.    Let me ask it this way.  Is it possible

        23     to have EDTA or any other compound left over in the

        24     column that you use for the chromatography stage?

        25            A.    I'm sorry, you mean ghosting, like -- you

        26     mean like spirit.

        27            Q.    Yes.

        28            A.    Yes, there is.  There is such a
 


                                                                   149
         1     phenomenon.

         2            Q.    Describe briefly what that is?

         3            A.    Well, if you -- let's say you inject into

         4     this equipment a lot -- relatively large amount of

         5     EDTA, let's say it comes out with a reading of 20 and

         6     then you make -- right after that, you make another

         7     injection or what should be a negative, a blank, for

         8     instance, and there you see a peak, but instead of

         9     being 20 it's between one and two.

        10                  That is very much likely or -- Well it's

        11     sufficiently likely to be a ghost, that what happened

        12     in the first one that some of the EDTA got stuck on

        13     the injection side or somewhere along the line and the

        14     second injection that came with it cleared it off,

        15     pushed it out and showed it up.

        16                    But I have never seen ghosting that is

        17     more than ten percent, it's almost always less than

        18     ten percent of the previous injection.

        19                  So unless there is an injection before

        20     that which is at least ten times as high as a little

        21     bit that shows up, I don't believe that this could be

        22     a ghost.  There's no way in here anything that --

        23     looks like it was just injected before and was very

        24     high.

        25            Q.    So is it your opinion that the two sock

        26     stains and the three gate stains that tested positive

        27     for EDTA, were not due to ghosting?

        28            A.    That is my opinion, yes.
 


                                                                   150
