        12            Q.    It's -- well, there are many scientists

        13     who will say the peak should be at least three times

        14     the height of the noise, true?

        15            A.    For what purpose?

        16            Q.    For determining whether a peak should

        17     even be called a peak, Doctor.

        18            A.    Well, not anymore, that's not the

        19     standard way of measuring noise, by comparing noise

        20     with signals as such.  But you use a statistical

        21     approach.

        22            Q.    Um-hum.  What's your statistical

        23     approach?

        24            A.    That you average this noise.  And when

        25     you do that, you get an average and variations around

        26     it.

        27                  And the unit of variations is called a

        28     standard deviation.
 


                                                                   169
         1                  And what you're -- what you look for --

         2     at least what I look for, and my colleagues look for,

         3     is three standard deviations above noise is an

         4     acceptable detection limit.  In some cases, two

         5     standard units.

         6            Q.    In case -- did you actually do the

         7     calculations and running all that out?

