        11            A.    They certainly should, yes.

        12            Q.    And you're not an experienced operator of

        13     the machine, are you?

        14            A.    Well, I'm not, but I know a lot about it,

        15     too.

        16            Q.    Well, you're somebody that's testified in

        17     court a lot; isn't that right, Doctor?

        18            A.    No, not because of that.

        19                  I've done an awful lot of LCM gas

        20     chromatography and ghosting occurs in all molds.  It's

        21     nothing special about this.

        22            Q.    And going back to the graph we have here

        23     with the mountain and the molehill, if Roger Martz is

        24     correct that he was using more blood in the evidence

        25     system than in the control sample, then you cannot

        26     tell this jury that this molehill is blood containing

        27     EDTA from a purple top test tube, can you, Doctor?

        28            A.    Well, I'm telling you he didn't -- he
 


                                                                   185
         1     couldn't have had any idea of how much blood he used

         2     in --

         3            Q.    Just follow -- just answer my question

         4     with my hypothetical.  If he's right --

         5            A.    If you bring it into the question.  Could

         6     you put that in there.

         7            Q.    Sure.

         8                  If Roger Martz is correct that he was

         9     using more blood in the evidence sample than he was in

        10     this control sample, is -- that is more in the

        11     molehill than in the mountain?

        12            A.    Um-hum.

        13            Q.    Then that molehill cannot represent blood

        14     from a purple top test tube, can it?

        15            A.    He can still do that if the EDTA degraded

        16     over the period of time since it was placed wherever

        17     it was.

        18            Q.    But you've done no experiment to

        19     determine how fast EDTA degrades, have you, Doctor?

        20            A.    Not how fast it degrades, but it does

        21     degrade.  It's a well known fact.

        22            Q.    You don't know at what rate it degrades

        23     at?

        24            A.    Well, in strong ultraviolet light like

        25     sunlight, pretty rapidly, but I haven't got any -- how

        26     fast I can tell you that.

        27            Q.    There's no literature in the forensic

        28     field showing how fast EDTA degrades in blood, is
 


                                                                   186
         1     there, Doctor?

         2            A.    It's not in the forensic field.  This is

         3     what is done in the environmental chemistry field,

         4     which really is forensic, but not like this, no.

         5            Q.    Isn't it the case, Dr. Rieders, that

         6     Agent Martz testified that -- excuse me, Agent Martz

         7     tested some other blood containing EDTA that was two

         8     years old, and he still obtained this mountain kind of

         9     result from that two-year old blood, true?

        10            A.    Oh, yeah, sure.

        11            Q.    So we know that it still shows up a

        12     couple years later, right?

        13            A.    If it's frozen in the dark, yes.

        14            Q.    So you're saying maybe environmental

        15     conditions might somehow explain how this mountain

        16     turned out to be a molehill; is that what you're

        17     saying?

        18            A.    No, no, no, that's not what I'm saying.

        19                  I'm saying if Roger Martz is correct that

        20     the amount of blood that he used to get that little

        21     molehill down there was less than the amount of blood

        22     that he used, if he's correct in that, where he got

        23     the mountain then that blood, the little molehill

        24     blood, came from an area that was outdoors, dry, wet

        25     when it rained, exposed to the sun, exposed to the

        26     elements, and then it was collected, and it is during

        27     that period that it meets the condition of the

        28     degradation that has been tested in EPA world.
 


                                                                   187
         1            Q.    You're saying it may be another

         2     explanation for how the mountain gets down to the

         3     molehill?

         4            A.    No, I don't think so.  I think my

         5     explanation is much more correct.

         6            Q.    This one you're looking at right here,

         7     these are the socks, Doctor, these socks were

         8     collected the day after the murders, they were in a

